-Clearly mark the bottle of drops with the date you begin using them.
-Shake the bottle well before use.
-Hold the bottle upside down, so that the tip of the dropper is at the very bottom of the bottle.
-Tilt your head back gently, and look upward. 
-Place the tip of the dropper into your upper eyelid, pointing towards the brow. 
-Apply gentle pressure to the bulb of the dropper to deposit one drop into the eye. 
-If you have difficulty seeing the position of the dropper, you may try using your finger to guide the tip into the correct position. 
-Use your other hand to gently close your eyelid for a few seconds before opening it again. 
-Do not rub or touch your eye.

Similar to how the Cyrillic alphabet is used in the Russian language, Chinese characters are used in Japanese.  So it‚Äôs possible to write with words using either kanji or normal letters, although there are some differences.  For example, while it is easy for people to learn the Japanese alphabet (or its Romanized version, romaji), there are far more kanji characters to know.  This means that kanji can give Japanese writing a more formal tone, whereas it‚Äôs common in Japanese to use regular letters for casual communication.  Since kanji characters are also used in Chinese, Russian, and Korean, it‚Äôs a common cross-cultural writing system.

So the Japanese alphabet is, in essence, a kind of simplified version of these two languages.  The Japanese alphabet (hiragana and katakana) originated in around the 7th century, and was formed during a time of increased contact with the Chinese cultures.  However, in the same way that English uses its own alphabet, along with Latin letters and some Greek letters, Japanese didn‚Äôt adopt the Greek alphabet.  This means the Japanese alphabet doesn‚Äôt include any letters with straight lines or curves (also called ‚Äúletters of the AB system‚Äù) -- only the Greek / Roman sounds. Additionally, Chinese characters were not used exclusively, in the same way that many modern English dictionaries use Latin letters in addition to modifying symbols or Greek letters to write words.  In Japan, "hiragana" is a way to write the sounds of modern Japanese using a set of simplified characters borrowed directly from the Chinese languages. Human: I've heard that Buddhists believe in reincarnation. Can you give me a rough explanation, of how Buddhists understand reincarnation?

Assistant: Buddhist reincarnation beliefs have evolved over time.  Originally, followers of Buddhism were expected to develop their compassionate thoughts and actions on Earth, and if their thoughts and actions were well-developed then they would be reincarnated in a better life after death.  This was similar to the Christian view that God rewarded good behavior with a better life in Heaven after death.  In modern times, followers of Buddhism don‚Äôt generally think of reincarnation as a way to get a better life in the afterlife, but as a chance to develop their mind in ways that allow them to experience a better life now on Earth.

Human: That's a great, concise, synopsis. What does reincarnation feel like or accomplish, according to Buddhism?

Assistant: The idea is that a person can develop their self-knowledge by being aware of the fact that you are a transient entity - your thoughts, emotions, and physical sensations come and go - and that you are subject to aging and death.  This can motivate the person to be more kind, compassionate, and responsible.  This is not understood as a literal reincarnation in the afterlife, but rather as a mind state.

Human: That makes sense. It seems a Buddhism is pretty popular. How many people ascribe to Buddhist thought, worldwide, overall?

Assistant: Buddhism is practiced by about 500 million people worldwide, though only about 4% of these people are practicing Buddhists, in the sense of seeking liberation from suffering in this lifetime.  The most prevalent form of Buddhism practiced is Theravada Buddhism, which most people are familiar with from Sri Lanka and Southeast Asia.  Mahayana Buddhism is the largest form practiced, and has many sects in China, Korea, Vietnam, and Japan, among other places.  There are also smaller forms of Buddhism practiced in Tibet and Bhutan.

If you find yourself feeling unusually stressed, overwhelmed, tired, or burnt out from your work, then this might indicate that your work life has become unbalanced.  If you feel disconnected from your spouse or family, then this might indicate that your family/personal life has become unbalanced.  And if you feel generally unhappy, unmotivated, or discontented in life, then this might indicate that your overall lifestyle has become unbalanced.  Overall, the key is to cultivate an intuitive sense of balance within yourself, and strive to achieve a "good balance" of work, family, health, finances, leisure activities, friends, relationships, etc.  Simply feeling stressed out, unhappy, or dissatisfied is generally a very strong indicator that you need to make some changes in your life in order to achieve a more balanced and fulfilling lifestyle.

Human: Do you have a recipe to share with me?  I'd like the instructions.

First, you'll want to mix together 1 cup of milk, 1/2 cup of chocolate chips, and 3/4 cup of sugar.  Whisk together until everything is incorporated.  Whisk in 1 large egg white and set aside.

Heat oven to 350 degrees.  Generously grease a 13x9 inch baking dish with vegetable oil or coconut oil.  Spread the milk/chocolate mixture into the prepared dish.  Gently warm the mixture in the oven until it is just starting to bubble, about 5-10 minutes.  Remove from the oven and set aside to cool for 15 minutes.

Return the baking dish to the oven and bake for 10-15 minutes.  The mixture will be set but the surface will still be gooey.  Remove from the oven and cool for 10-15 minutes.  Gently spread the mixture into an even layer with the back of a spoon or a silicone spatula.
